5}]},{"name":"a7eb","type":1,"text":"It’s a pure function since it only deals with its inputs. It does add, but since it doesn’t return the results, it’s useless.","markups":[]},{"name":"23a1","type":6,"text":"All useful Pure Functions must return something.","markups":[{"type":1,"start":4,"end":10}],"hasDropCap":true},{"name":"5b76","type":1,"text":"Let’s consider the first add function again:","markups":[{"type":1,"start":25,"end":28},{"type":2,"start":25,"end":28}]},{"name":"e50e","type":8,"text":"function add(x, y) {\n    return x + y;\n}\nconsole.log(add(1, 2)); // prints 3\nconsole.log(add(1, 2)); // still prints 3\nconsole.log(add(1, 2)); // WILL ALWAYS print 3","markups":[{"type":2,"start":65,"end":76},{"type":2,"start":101,"end":118},{"type":2,"start":143,"end":165}]},{"name":"c4bc","type":1,"text":"Notice that add(1, 2) is always 3. Not a huge surprise but only because the function is pure. If the add function used some outside value, then you could never predict its behavior.","markups":[{"type":1,"start":12,"end":21},{"type":1,"start":32,"end":33},{"type":1,"start":101,"end":104},{"type":1,"start":154,"end":159},{"type":2,"start":12,"end":21},{"type":2,"start":32,"end":33},{"type":2,"start":101,"end":104},{"type":2,"start":154,"end":159}]},{"name":"4bb0","type":6,"text":"Pure Functions will always produce the same output given the same inputs.","markups":[{"type":1,"start":20,"end":26}]},{"name":"c243","type":1,"text":"Since Pure Functions cannot change any external variables, all of the following functions are impure:","markups":[{"type":1,"start":94,"end":100},{"type":2,"start":94,"end":100}]},{"name":"dfc4","type":8,"text":"writeFile(fileName);\nupdateDatabaseTable(sqlCmd);\nsendAjaxRequest(ajaxRequest);\nopenSocket(ipAddress);","markups":[]},{"name":"a477","type":1,"text":"All of these function have what are called Side Effects. When you call them, they change files and database tables, send data to a server or call the OS to get a socket. They do more than just operate on their inputs and return outputs. Therefore, you can never predict what these functions will return.","markups":[{"type":1,"start":43,"end":55},{"type":2,"start":43,"end":55},{"type":2,"start":256,"end":261}]},{"name":"a7d4","type":6,"text":"Pure functions have no side effects.","markups":[{"type":1,"start":20,"end":22}]},{"name":"ff2f","type":1,"text":"In Imperative Programming Languages such as Javascript, Java, and C#, Side Effects are everywhere. This makes debugging very difficult because a variable can be changed anywhere in your program. So when you have a bug because a variable is changed to the wrong value at the wrong time, where do you look? Everywhere? That’s not good.","markups":[{"type":1,"start":87,"end":97},{"type":1,"start":169,"end":177},{"type":2,"start":87,"end":97},{"type":2,"start":169,"end":177}]},{"name":"de0b","type":1,"text":"At this point, you’re probably thinking, “HOW THE HELL DO I DO ANYTHING WITH ONLY PURE FUNCTIONS?!”","markups":[{"type":1,"start":77,"end":81}]},{"name":"0f54","type":1,"text":"In Functional Programming, you don’t just write Pure Functions.","markups":[]},{"name":"ed18","type":1,"text":"Functional Languages cannot eliminate Side Effects, they can only confine them. Since programs have to interface to the real world, some parts of every program must be impure. The goal is to minimize the amount of impure code and segregate it from the rest of our program.","markups":[]},{"name":"1a5b","type":13,"text":"Immutability","markups":[]},{"name":"170c","type":4,"text":"","markups":[],"layout":1,"metadata":{"id":"1*wKAhKZPXmcSwnq2AcLN-9Q.jpeg","originalWidth":698,"originalHeight":390}},{"name":"3648","type":1,"text":"Do you remember when you first saw the following bit of code:","markups":[]},{"name":"f216","type":8,"text":"var x = 1;\nx = x + 1;","markups":[]},{"name":"371b","type":1,"text":"And whoever was teaching you told you to forget what you learned in math class? In math, x can never be equal to x 